window.TEST_DATA = {
"1": {"questext": "The Simon Commission was sent to India to review the working of which Act and report on India's constitutional progress?", "options": ["Indian Councils Act, 1909", "Government of India Act, 1919", "Government of India Act, 1935", "Indian Independence Act, 1947"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Government of India Act, 1919</b><br><br>The Simon Commission was sent to India to review the working of the <b>Government of India Act, 1919</b> and to report on India's constitutional progress for introducing constitutional reforms as had been promised. The Act of 1919 had provided that a <b>Constitutional Commission</b> would be appointed ten years after the passing of the Act to examine the extent to which India had progressed towards responsible government.", "expimage": ""},
"2": {"questext": "Why did the Conservative Government of Britain appoint the Simon Commission two years earlier than scheduled, on 8 November 1927?", "options": ["To please the Indian National Congress", "To fear that the Labour Party Government could appoint a Commission with pro-India members", "To speed up the process of transfer of power", "To implement the recommendations of the Nehru Report"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>To fear that the Labour Party Government could appoint a Commission with pro-India members</b><br><br>The Commission should have been appointed after 10 years (i.e., 1929), but the then <b>Conservative Government</b> of Britain appointed the Simon Commission two years earlier, on <b>8 November 1927</b>, because it feared that after two years the <b>Labour Party Government</b> could appoint a statutory Commission having pro-India members. The Simon Commission was appointed by the State Secretary <b>Birkenhead</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"3": {"questext": "Who was the chairman of the Simon Commission, and why was it boycotted as a 'White Commission'?", "options": ["Lord Birkenhead; because it delayed the transfer of power", "Sir John Simon; because all seven members were British", "Lord Irwin; because it ignored Congress demands", "Ramsay MacDonald; because it favoured the Muslim League"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Sir John Simon; because all seven members were British</b><br><br>The Simon Commission was constituted under the chairmanship of <b>Sir John Simon</b> and had seven members. The fact that all the seven members were British became the reason for opposition, hence it was boycotted by calling it a <b>'White Commission'</b>. The commission visited India twice between <b>1928-29</b> and submitted its report in <b>May 1930</b>, which was to be considered in the Round Table Conference held in London.", "expimage": ""},
"4": {"questext": "Which of the following was NOT an objective of the Simon Commission?", "options": ["To delay the process of transfer of power", "To give political autonomy without economic autonomy", "To report on the relationship between native states and the British Government", "To grant complete independence to India immediately"], "correct": "4", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>To grant complete independence to India immediately</b><br><br>The objectives of the Simon Commission included: to <b>delay the process of transfer of power</b> and review the working of the Government of India Act, 1919; to report on the future relationship between the <b>native states</b> and the British Government (for which the <b>Butler Committee</b> was appointed); to exhibit that the British were sincere in giving self-rule but that Indians could not reach consensus on power-sharing; and to give <b>political autonomy without economic autonomy</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"5": {"questext": "Which recommendation was made by the Simon Commission regarding Diarchy?", "options": ["Continuation of Diarchy with minor changes", "Abolition of Diarchy and a federal government with maximum provincial autonomy", "Extension of Diarchy to the Centre", "Replacement of Diarchy with Dominion Status"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Abolition of Diarchy and a federal government with maximum provincial autonomy</b><br><br>The Simon Commission recommended the <b>abolition of Diarchy</b> and setting up of a <b>federal form of government</b> with maximum autonomy to the provinces. A federal constitution was to be made, but Indians would not be given representation at the Centre, and no changes were proposed in the <b>Central Executive</b>. It also recommended separation of <b>Burma's</b> administration from India, an increase in provincial legislative council members, and extension of the franchise from <b>2.8% to 10-15%</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"6": {"questext": "The Simon Commission recommended that the tendency to appoint a commission after every how many years for constitutional reforms should be curtailed?", "options": ["5 years", "10 years", "15 years", "20 years"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>10 years</b><br><br>The Simon Commission recommended that the tendency to appoint a commission after every <b>10 years</b> to bring new constitutional reforms was to be curtailed and not encouraged. This was one of its formal recommendations alongside the abolition of Diarchy, provincial autonomy, and separation of Burma from Indian administration.", "expimage": ""},
"7": {"questext": "Which of the following was a limitation of the Simon Commission?", "options": ["It proposed universal franchise", "It had no Indian members and proposed no financial devolution", "It abolished separate electorates", "It strengthened the Governor-General's powers significantly"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>It had no Indian members and proposed no financial devolution</b><br><br>The limitations of the Simon Commission were: there were <b>no Indian members</b> in the Commission; no <b>universal franchise</b> was proposed; the position of the <b>Governor-General</b> remained unaffected; there was no provision to abolish separate electorates but rather it was extended to other communities; and <b>no financial devolution</b> was proposed.", "expimage": ""},
"8": {"questext": "When did the Simon Commission arrive in India, and which city did it land in first?", "options": ["3rd February 1928, Mumbai", "27th December 1927, Madras", "8th November 1927, Delhi", "12th March 1928, Calcutta"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>3rd February 1928, Mumbai</b><br><br>The Simon Commission arrived in Mumbai on <b>3rd February, 1928</b> and was met with intense protests. A decision to completely boycott the Simon Commission had already been taken at the <b>Congress session held in Madras on 27 December 1927</b>, which was chaired by <b>M.A. Ansari</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"9": {"questext": "Which political parties boycotted the Simon Commission?", "options": ["Only the Indian National Congress", "Liberal Federation, Indian Industrial Commercial Congress, Hindu Mahasabha, Kisan Mazdoor Party, Jinnah group", "Only the Muslim League led by Mohammad Shafi", "Only the Justice Party and Unionist Party of Punjab"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Liberal Federation, Indian Industrial Commercial Congress, Hindu Mahasabha, Kisan Mazdoor Party, Jinnah group</b><br><br>Among the then political parties, the <b>Liberal Federation, Indian Industrial Commercial Congress, Hindu Mahasabha, Kisan Mazdoor Party, and Jinnah group</b> boycotted the Commission. There was protest against it all over India. Only the <b>Muslim League led by Mohammad Shafi</b>, the <b>Justice Party</b>, the <b>All India Untouchable Association</b>, and the <b>Unionist Party of Punjab</b> did not oppose it.", "expimage": ""},
"10": {"questext": "Who coined the famous slogan 'SIMON GO BACK'?", "options": ["M.A. Ansari", "Yusuf Meherali", "Lala Lajpat Rai", "Bhagat Singh"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Yusuf Meherali</b><br><br><b>Yusuf Meherali</b> coined the famous slogan <b>'Simon Go Back'</b> which became the unofficial war cry of the protests against the Simon Commission. The recommendations of the Simon Commission were later discussed in the three <b>Round Table Conferences</b>, and based on these, the <b>Government of India Act, 1935</b> was prepared. The biggest effect of the Simon Commission on the national movement was that it united different voices across the Indian political spectrum, giving new life and vigour to the freedom struggle.", "expimage": ""},
"11": {"questext": "Lala Lajpat Rai died as a result of injuries sustained while protesting against the Simon Commission. Who was the officer responsible for ordering the lathi charge, and who was he assassinated by?", "options": ["Lord Irwin; assassinated by Subhash Chandra Bose", "John Saunders; assassinated by Bhagat Singh and Rajguru", "James Scott; assassinated by Chandrashekhar Azad", "Lord Willingdon; assassinated by Sukhdev"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>John Saunders; assassinated by Bhagat Singh and Rajguru</b><br><br>Lala Lajpat Rai was severely injured after receiving a lathi blow to his head while protesting against the Simon Commission and died as a result. The country was hit by shock and disgust, culminating in revolutionary nationalists murdering <b>John Saunders</b>, the officer who ordered the lathi charge. On <b>17 December 1928</b>, <b>Bhagat Singh and Rajguru</b> shot John Saunders, for which Bhagat Singh, Rajguru and <b>Sukhdev</b> were hanged on <b>23 March 1931</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"12": {"questext": "In the context of the Nehru Report (1928), which Secretary of State for India challenged Indians to draft an acceptable constitution?", "options": ["Lord Birkenhead", "Samuel Hoare", "Lord Linlithgow", "Ramsay MacDonald"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Lord Birkenhead</b><br><br>At the time of the appointment of the Simon Commission, <b>Lord Birkenhead</b>, the Secretary of State for India, challenged Indians to draft a constitution acceptable to all significant political parties. This challenge implied that Indians could not produce a constitution widely accepted by leaders of the various Indian communities. In response, a committee under the chairmanship of <b>Motilal Nehru</b> was formed.", "expimage": ""},
"13": {"questext": "At which session was the resolution passed to draft a constitution providing for a fully responsible government, in response to Birkenhead's challenge?", "options": ["First All Party Conference, Delhi, February 1928", "Second All Party Conference, Bombay, May 1928", "Congress session, Madras, December 1927", "Lahore session, December 1929"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>First All Party Conference, Delhi, February 1928</b><br><br>Indian leaders accepted Birkenhead's challenge, and a resolution was passed in the <b>first all party conference</b> held in <b>Delhi in February 1928</b>, which planned to create a constitution providing for a fully responsible government. Subsequently, at the <b>Second All Party Conference</b> held in <b>Bombay in May 1928</b>, an eight-member committee was set up under the chairmanship of <b>Motilal Nehru</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"14": {"questext": "Which of the following was NOT a member of Motilal Nehru's committee that drafted the Nehru Report?", "options": ["Tej Bahadur Sapru", "Subhash Chandra Bose", "Mohammad Ali Jinnah", "Shoaib Qureshi"], "correct": "3", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Mohammad Ali Jinnah</b><br><br>The members of Motilal Nehru's committee included <b>Tej Bahadur Sapru, Subhash Chandra Bose, M.S. Rainey, Mangal Singh, Ali Imam, G.R. Pradhan, and Shoaib Qureshi</b>, among others. The committee headed by <b>Motilal Nehru</b> submitted its report in <b>August 1928</b>, which came to be known as the <b>'Nehru Report'</b>. This report contained a blueprint for the new Dominion Constitution of India.", "expimage": ""},
"15": {"questext": "Which of the following was a key recommendation of the Nehru Committee regarding the status and character of India?", "options": ["Complete independence with a monarchy", "Dominion status on the lines of self-governing dominions, and India as a secular state", "Princely rule under British suzerainty", "A unitary state with no fundamental rights"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Dominion status on the lines of self-governing dominions, and India as a secular state</b><br><br>The Nehru Committee recommended <b>Dominion status</b> on the lines of self-governing dominions within the British empire. It also recommended that <b>India was to be a secular state</b> with <b>nineteen fundamental rights</b>, including equal rights for women, right to form unions, and universal adult suffrage. India was to be a <b>federation</b> with a <b>bicameral legislature</b> at the centre, with the Cabinet answerable to the House.", "expimage": ""},
"16": {"questext": "Regarding provincial reorganization, what did the Nehru Report recommend for Sindh and the North-West Frontier Province?", "options": ["Sindh should merge with Punjab; NWFP should remain a Chief Commissioner's province", "Sindh should be separated from Bombay as a separate province; NWFP should get the same statutory status as other provinces", "Both should be merged into a single new province", "Both should be placed directly under the Governor-General"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Sindh should be separated from Bombay as a separate province; NWFP should get the same statutory status as other provinces</b><br><br>The Nehru Report recommended that <b>Sindh</b> should be separated from Bombay and made a separate province, and that the <b>North-West Frontier Province</b> should be given the same statutory status as other provinces of British India. It also recommended a <b>federal government</b> with <b>residuary powers</b> vested in the Centre.", "expimage": ""},
"17": {"questext": "Regarding electorates and minorities, what did the Nehru Report provide?", "options": ["Separate electorates for all minority communities", "No separate electorates, but reservation of minority seats where a minority was at least ten percent of the population", "Only reservation for Muslims, not other minorities", "Complete abolition of all reservations"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>No separate electorates, but reservation of minority seats where a minority was at least ten percent of the population</b><br><br>The Nehru Report did not provide <b>separate electorates</b> for any community or minorities. However, it did allow for the <b>reservation of minority seats</b> in provinces having a minority of at least <b>ten percent</b>. It also ensured the rights and privileges of the <b>native states</b> would be maintained.", "expimage": ""},
"18": {"questext": "According to the Nehru Report, what was to be the position of the Governor-General, and which new institutions were proposed?", "options": ["Executive head with veto power; only a Supreme Court was proposed", "Only a constitutional head; a Defence Committee, Supreme Court, and Public Service Commission were to be established", "Ceremonial head with no institutional changes proposed", "Commander-in-chief with expanded emergency powers"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Only a constitutional head; a Defence Committee, Supreme Court, and Public Service Commission were to be established</b><br><br>The Nehru Report recommended that the position of the <b>Governor General</b> would remain only that of a <b>constitutional head</b>. A <b>Defence Committee, Supreme Court, and Public Service Commission</b> were to be established in India. Provisions were also made for the formation of provinces on a <b>linguistic basis</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"19": {"questext": "Which young Congress leaders wanted Purna Swaraj instead of Dominion Status as the goal of Congress, leading to differences at the 1928 Calcutta session?", "options": ["Motilal Nehru, Tej Bahadur Sapru, M.A. Ansari", "Subhash Chandra Bose, Jawaharlal Nehru, Satyamurti", "Sardar Patel, Rajendra Prasad, C. Rajagopalachari", "Bhagat Singh, Rajguru, Sukhdev"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Subhash Chandra Bose, Jawaharlal Nehru, Satyamurti</b><br><br>Young leaders in the Congress like <b>Subhash Chandra Bose, Jawaharlal Nehru, and Satyamurti</b> wanted to make <b>Purna Swaraj</b> the goal of the Congress instead of Dominion Status. Differences arose within the Congress on this issue at the <b>Calcutta session of 1928</b>, and the All Party Conference could not accept the report. Subsequently, Bose, Nehru and Satyamurti founded the <b>All India Independence League in 1928</b> to achieve complete independence.", "expimage": ""},
"20": {"questext": "What ultimatum did the Congress give to the British regarding the Nehru Report?", "options": ["Accept it by 31 December 1929 or Congress would launch a popular movement", "Accept it immediately or Congress would boycott all elections", "Accept it by 1930 or Congress would dissolve itself", "Accept it within a week or Congress would declare war"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Accept it by 31 December 1929 or Congress would launch a popular movement</b><br><br>Congress gave an ultimatum to the British that if the Government did not accept the <b>'Nehru Report'</b> by <b>31st December, 1929</b>, the Congress would launch a popular movement. Meanwhile, at the <b>All-Parties Conference held in Calcutta in December 1928</b> to consider the Nehru Report, Jinnah, on behalf of the Muslim League, proposed certain amendments to it.", "expimage": ""},
"21": {"questext": "Which amendments did Jinnah propose on behalf of the Muslim League to the Nehru Report at the Calcutta All-Parties Conference (December 1928)?", "options": ["Abolition of all electorates and a unitary government", "Retention of separate electorates for Muslims and one-third representation in the Central Legislature", "Complete merger of Sindh with Punjab", "Universal adult suffrage without any reservations"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Retention of separate electorates for Muslims and one-third representation in the Central Legislature</b><br><br>Jinnah proposed: retention of <b>separate electorates for Muslims</b>; <b>one-third representation</b> to Muslims in the Central Legislature; reservation to Muslims in <b>Bengal and Punjab</b> legislatures proportionate to their population until adult suffrage was established; and <b>residual powers to provinces</b>. These demands were not accommodated, and Jinnah went to the <b>Shafi faction</b> of the Muslim League, which gave <b>fourteen points</b> in March 1929.", "expimage": ""},
"22": {"questext": "At the Delhi session of the Muslim League in December 1927, which four demands were proposed to be added to the draft Constitution?", "options": ["Separate Muslim state, no reservations, unitary government, no NWFP autonomy", "Sindh as a separate state, NWFP given equal status, 1/3 representation for Muslims in central legislature, population-based representation in Punjab and Bengal", "Abolition of separate electorates entirely", "Full merger of all princely states into British India"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Sindh as a separate state, NWFP given equal status, 1/3 representation for Muslims in central legislature, population-based representation in Punjab and Bengal</b><br><br>In December 1927, prominent Muslim leaders at the <b>Delhi session</b> of the Muslim League demanded four points: <b>Sindh</b> should be made a separate state; the <b>North West Frontier Province</b> should be given the same status as other provinces; Muslims should get <b>1/3 representation</b> in the central legislature; and the ratio of representation in <b>Punjab and Bengal</b> should be in accordance with population while existing seat reservations for Muslims elsewhere should remain intact.", "expimage": ""},
"23": {"questext": "Jinnah's Fourteen Points Formula was presented in which month and year?", "options": ["December 1928", "March 1929", "December 1929", "January 1930"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>March 1929</b><br><br>Jinnah's <b>Fourteen Points Formula</b> was presented in <b>March 1929</b>. It included demands such as a <b>Federal Constitution</b> with residual powers to provinces, no constitutional amendment without concurrence of the states, reservation for Muslims in State Services and local self-governing bodies, continuation of <b>separate electorates</b>, and <b>provincial autonomy</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"24": {"questext": "Which of the following was among Jinnah's Fourteen Points (March 1929)?", "options": ["Separation of Sindh from Bombay as a distinct province and one-third Muslim representation in cabinets", "Abolition of separate electorates in all provinces", "Merger of Baluchistan with Punjab", "Reduction of Muslim representation in Bengal and Punjab"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Separation of Sindh from Bombay as a distinct province and one-third Muslim representation in cabinets</b><br><br>Jinnah's Fourteen Points included: <b>separation of Sindh</b> from Bombay as a distinct province; no bill to be passed if three-fourths of a minority community considered it against their interests; constitutional reforms in the <b>North West Frontier Province and Baluchistan</b>; <b>one-third representation</b> of Muslims in cabinets at the Centre and provinces; and protection of Muslim rights in <b>religion, culture, education and language</b>. It also demanded full religious freedom for all communities and that territorial redistribution not affect the Muslim majority in Punjab, Bengal and NWFP.", "expimage": ""},
"25": {"questext": "Who presided over the Lahore Session of the Congress in December 1929, at which the 'Poorna Swaraj' resolution was passed?", "options": ["Motilal Nehru", "Jawaharlal Nehru", "M.A. Ansari", "Subhash Chandra Bose"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b><br><br>In December 1929, Congress held its annual session at <b>Lahore</b>, which was presided over by <b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b>. In this session, Congress passed a historic resolution declaring <b>'Poorna Swaraj'</b> or complete independence as its only aim. Since the Declaration of Independence was officially promulgated on <b>26th January 1930</b>, it was decided to celebrate <b>26th January</b> each year as Independence Day.", "expimage": ""},
"26": {"questext": "What symbolic act did Jawaharlal Nehru perform at midnight on 31 December 1929 on the banks of the River Ravi?", "options": ["He signed the Nehru Report", "He hoisted the tricolour flag amid slogans of Purna Swaraj", "He launched the Civil Disobedience Movement", "He announced the Dandi March"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>He hoisted the tricolour flag amid slogans of Purna Swaraj</b><br><br>At midnight on <b>31 December 1929</b>, on the banks of the <b>River Ravi</b>, Congress President <b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b> hoisted the tricolour flag, a symbol of Indian independence, amid slogans of <b>Purna Swaraj, Vande Mataram, and Inquilab Zindabad</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"27": {"questext": "Which of the following resolutions was NOT passed at the Lahore Session of Congress (1929)?", "options": ["The Nehru Committee report was declared to have lapsed", "Gandhi was authorized to launch the Civil Disobedience Movement", "Congress decided to participate in the First Round Table Conference", "26 January 1930 was observed as Poorna Swaraj Day"], "correct": "3", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Congress decided to participate in the First Round Table Conference</b><br><br>At the Lahore session, Congress declared that the <b>Nehru Committee report</b> had now lapsed and dominion status was no longer acceptable; a <b>Poorna Swaraj resolution</b> was passed; the Congress decided to launch a <b>Civil Disobedience Movement</b>; <b>Gandhi</b> was authorized to launch it at the time and manner of his choice; <b>26 January 1930</b> was observed as Poorna Swaraj Day; and the Congress decided <b>NOT to participate</b> in the First Round Table Conference convened to discuss Simon Commission proposals.", "expimage": ""},
"28": {"questext": "Gandhiji's 11 Point demands were presented on 31 January 1930 before which two figures?", "options": ["Viceroy Lord Irwin and British PM Ramsay MacDonald", "Viceroy Lord Willingdon and Winston Churchill", "Lord Birkenhead and Sir John Simon", "Lord Linlithgow and Samuel Hoare"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Viceroy Lord Irwin and British PM Ramsay MacDonald</b><br><br>Gandhiji presented <b>11 Point demands</b> before Viceroy <b>Lord Irwin</b> and British Prime Minister <b>Ramsay MacDonald</b> on <b>31 January 1930</b>. These demands were presented by Gandhiji in his paper <b>'Young India'</b>. The demands included a 50 percent reduction in military expenditure, release of political prisoners, and reforms in the Criminal Intelligence Department, among others.", "expimage": ""},
"29": {"questext": "Which of the following was among Gandhiji's 11 Point demands presented in January 1930?", "options": ["Abolition of the Zamindari system", "End of salt tax and government monopoly on salt", "Introduction of universal adult franchise", "Creation of a bicameral legislature"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>End of salt tax and government monopoly on salt</b><br><br>Among Gandhiji's 11 Point demands were: reduction of the <b>rupee-sterling exchange ratio</b> to 1 shilling 4 pence, protection to the <b>textile industry</b>, reservation of Indian beaches for Indians, reduction in <b>land tax</b>, and to <b>end salt tax</b> and government monopoly on salt. Other demands included release of political prisoners, reform of the Criminal Intelligence Department, and amendment of arms laws to permit licenses for self-defense.", "expimage": ""},
"30": {"questext": "Which of the following was a factor leading to the Civil Disobedience Movement (1930)?", "options": ["Passage of the Rowlatt Act", "The Great Depression of 1929 and rejection of Gandhi's 11-point demands", "The formation of the Muslim League", "The Jallianwala Bagh massacre"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The Great Depression of 1929 and rejection of Gandhi's 11-point demands</b><br><br>Factors leading to the Civil Disobedience Movement included: disappointment with the 'all white' <b>Simon Commission</b>; the <b>Great Depression of 1929</b>, which increased hardships through price rise and unemployment; confrontation between the <b>Capitalist class</b> and colonial masters; and the fact that Congress had declared complete independence its final aim at the <b>Lahore Session (1929)</b>, while Gandhi's compromise offer of the <b>11-point demands</b> was not accepted by Lord Irwin.", "expimage": ""},
"31": {"questext": "The Dandi March began on 12th March 1930 from Ahmedabad. How many members accompanied Gandhi, and what did he write to Irwin?", "options": ["Seventy-eight members; 'I asked for bread, and got a stone in return'", "Fifty members; 'Do or Die'", "Hundred members; 'Freedom is our birthright'", "Twenty-five members; 'Simon Go Back'"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Seventy-eight members; 'I asked for bread, and got a stone in return'</b><br><br>On <b>12th March 1930</b>, Gandhi, along with a band of <b>seventy-eight members</b> of Sabarmati, marched from his headquarters in Ahmedabad to Dandi. Gandhiji wrote a letter to Irwin when his 11-point demands were not accepted, stating, <b>\"I asked for bread, and got a stone in return. The hours of waiting are over now.\"</b>", "expimage": ""},
"32": {"questext": "Gandhiji reached Dandi and broke the salt law on which date, after covering how many miles?", "options": ["5 April 1930 (arrival), 6 April 1930 (salt law broken); 240 miles", "1 April 1930 (arrival), 2 April 1930 (salt law broken); 200 miles", "10 April 1930 (arrival), 12 April 1930 (salt law broken); 300 miles", "6 April 1930 (arrival and salt law broken same day); 150 miles"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>5 April 1930 (arrival), 6 April 1930 (salt law broken); 240 miles</b><br><br>Gandhiji, along with his 78 followers, reached <b>Dandi</b> village on the coast of Gujarat on <b>5 April 1930</b>, after a long padayatra of <b>240 miles</b> from the Sabarmati Ashram — known as the <b>'Dandi March'</b>. He broke the salt law by picking up a handful of salt in Dandi on <b>6 April 1930</b>, an event also called the <b>'Salt Satyagraha'</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"33": {"questext": "Which future actions did Gandhi direct as part of the Dandi Programme?", "options": ["Boycott of civil disobedience of the salt law and picketing of foreign liquor and cloth shops", "Formation of a separate Muslim state", "Immediate armed rebellion against the British", "Nationwide industrial strikes only"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Boycott of civil disobedience of the salt law and picketing of foreign liquor and cloth shops</b><br><br>Gandhi's directions for future action included: wherever possible, civil disobedience of the <b>salt law</b> program should be started; <b>foreign liquor and cloth shops</b> should be picketed; lawyers should give up practice; and the public should boycott law courts and government servants should resign. All this was to be subject to the condition of <b>truth and non-violence</b>. Subhash Chandra Bose compared this campaign to <b>Napoleon's march from Elba to Paris</b> and Mussolini's <b>'Rome March'</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"34": {"questext": "Why was salt chosen as the symbol of protest in the Civil Disobedience Movement?", "options": ["Because it was used by nearly everyone in India and represented 8.2% of British tax revenue", "Because it was the most expensive commodity in India", "Because only the rich used salt", "Because it had no economic significance"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Because it was used by nearly everyone in India and represented 8.2% of British tax revenue</b><br><br>The salt tax was a symbolic choice since salt was used by nearly everyone in India, and an item of daily use could resonate more with all classes than an abstract demand for political rights. The salt tax represented <b>8.2%</b> of the British Raj's tax revenue and hurt the poorest Indians the most.", "expimage": ""},
"35": {"questext": "Who led the Salt March from Trichy (Tiruchirappalli) to Vedaranyam on the Tanjore coast in Tamil Nadu?", "options": ["C. Rajagopalachari", "K. Kelappan", "Sarojini Naidu", "Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>C. Rajagopalachari</b><br><br>In Tamil Nadu, Gandhian politician <b>C. Rajagopalachari</b> led a Salt March from Trichy to <b>Vedaranyam</b> on the Tanjore coast. In Malabar, <b>K. Kelappan</b>, leader of the Vaikom Satyagraha, carried out a Salt March from <b>Calicut to Pennar</b>. 'Shivirams' (on the lines of military camps) were established in various districts of <b>Andhra Pradesh</b> to serve as headquarters of the Salt Satyagraha.", "expimage": ""},
"36": {"questext": "The most powerful form of the Civil Disobedience Movement, involving an attack on a factory, was seen at which location?", "options": ["Dharasana in Bombay (present-day Gujarat)", "Peshawar in North-West Frontier Province", "Wardha in Central Provinces", "Karachi in Sindh"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Dharasana in Bombay (present-day Gujarat)</b><br><br>The most powerful form of the Civil Disobedience Movement was seen at <b>Dharasana</b>, where thousands of Satyagrahis along with <b>Sarojini Naidu, Mani Lal, and Imam Saheb</b> attacked a factory. An attempt was also made to break the salt law by travelling from <b>Sylhet in Assam</b> to the <b>Noakhali coast in Bengal</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"37": {"questext": "In the North-West Frontier Province, which organization led by Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan played an active role in the Civil Disobedience Movement, and what magazine did they publish?", "options": ["Khudai Khidmatgar or 'Lal Kurti'; 'Pakhtoon'", "Forward Bloc; 'Inquilab'", "Kisan Sabha; 'Harijan'", "Congress Socialist Party; 'Young India'"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Khudai Khidmatgar or 'Lal Kurti'; 'Pakhtoon'</b><br><br>Muslims of the North-West Frontier Province started the Civil Disobedience Movement under the leadership of <b>Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan (Frontier Gandhi)</b>. His organization, the <b>'Khudai Khidmatgar'</b> or <b>'Lal Kurti'</b>, played an active role and published a magazine called <b>'Pakhtoon'</b>. Troops of the <b>Garhwal Regiment</b> sent to Peshawar to suppress the agitators <b>refused to fire</b> on unarmed protesters.", "expimage": ""},
"38": {"questext": "Which 13-year-old Naga woman supported the Civil Disobedience Movement in the North-East and was later honoured by Nehru with the title 'Rani'?", "options": ["Sarojini Naidu", "Rani Gaidinliu", "Kasturba Gandhi", "Aruna Asaf Ali"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Rani Gaidinliu</b><br><br>The tribes of the North-East participated in the Civil Disobedience Movement with great enthusiasm. 13-year-old <b>Rani Gaidinliu</b>, a young Naga woman, supported the movement along with her Naga companions, and Nehru later honoured her with the title <b>'Rani'</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"39": {"questext": "How did the Civil Disobedience Movement differ from the Non-Cooperation Movement in terms of women's and Muslims' participation?", "options": ["Women's participation was unprecedented, but Muslim participation was less enthusiastic than before", "Both women's and Muslim participation decreased significantly", "Muslim participation increased while women's participation decreased", "Both remained exactly the same as the Non-Cooperation Movement"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Women's participation was unprecedented, but Muslim participation was less enthusiastic than before</b><br><br>The Civil Disobedience Movement saw <b>unprecedented participation of women</b>, a marked change from earlier movements where it was confined to a few elite women. It also received significant support from the <b>Indian capitalist class</b>. Peasant participation was significant but lesser than during the Non-Cooperation Movement, and <b>Muslim participation</b> was not very enthusiastic, except in the northwestern region under <b>Khan Abdul Gaffar Khan's Red Shirts</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"40": {"questext": "What was the Government's response to the Civil Disobedience Movement, and what did the Viceroy suggest in July 1930?", "options": ["The government remained passive throughout; no conference was suggested", "Initially ambivalent, then repression was unleashed; the Viceroy suggested a Round Table Conference", "The government immediately granted full independence", "The government banned only the Congress party without any repression"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Initially ambivalent, then repression was unleashed; the Viceroy suggested a Round Table Conference</b><br><br>The Government's initial attitude throughout 1930 was ambivalent, puzzled and perplexed; however, soon repression was unleashed upon volunteers, and ordinances banning civil liberties, including gagging of the press, were freely used. In <b>July 1930</b>, the <b>Viceroy</b> suggested a <b>Round Table Conference (RTC)</b> and reiterated the goal of dominion status.", "expimage": ""},
"41": {"questext": "Which of the following was part of the Programme of the Civil Disobedience Movement?", "options": ["Non-payment of taxes and boycott of courts by lawyers", "Formation of a separate legislature", "Armed insurrection against British troops", "Boycott of the salt satyagraha itself"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Non-payment of taxes and boycott of courts by lawyers</b><br><br>The Programme of the Civil Disobedience Movement included: boycott of government-aided educational institutions and offices; <b>boycott of courts</b> by lawyers; <b>non-payment of taxes</b>; violation of unjust laws; bonfires of foreign goods; picketing of liquor shops; protest marches; and <b>non-payment of rent and revenue</b> by farmers.", "expimage": ""},
"42": {"questext": "Who officially opened the First Round Table Conference on 12 November 1930, and who chaired it?", "options": ["Lord Irwin opened it; chaired by Ramsay MacDonald", "Lord Willingdon opened it; chaired by Winston Churchill", "Lord Linlithgow opened it; chaired by Samuel Hoare", "Sir John Simon opened it; chaired by Lord Birkenhead"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Lord Irwin opened it; chaired by Ramsay MacDonald</b><br><br>The First Round Table Conference (12 Nov 1930 - 19 Jan 1931) was the first-ever conference arranged between the British and Indians as equals. It was officially opened by <b>Lord Irwin</b> on 12 November 1930, in London, and chaired by British Prime Minister <b>Ramsay MacDonald</b>. While the Congress and most business leaders boycotted the First RTC, the <b>Muslim League, Hindu Mahasabha, Liberals, and Princes</b> attended it.", "expimage": ""},
"43": {"questext": "How many delegates attended the First Round Table Conference, and who represented the Dalit class?", "options": ["89 delegates; Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar", "46 delegates; C. Rajagopalachari", "120 delegates; Jawaharlal Nehru", "50 delegates; M.A. Jinnah"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>89 delegates; Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar</b><br><br>A total of <b>89 delegates</b> attended the First RTC, including <b>Jayakar and V.S. Moonje</b> (Hindu Mahasabha), <b>C.Y. Chintamani and T.V. Sapru</b> (Liberals), <b>Aga Khan, Muhammad Shafi, Jinnah, and Fazlul Haq</b> (Muslim League), <b>Sardar Sampoorna Singh</b> (Sikh), <b>K.T. Paul</b> (Anglo Indian), and <b>Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar</b> (Dalit class), along with 16 Naresh kings representing Native Princely States.", "expimage": ""},
"44": {"questext": "At the First Round Table Conference, which demand did Ambedkar raise, and who moved the idea of an All-India Federation?", "options": ["Ambedkar raised the demand for joint electorates; Jinnah moved the federation idea", "Ambedkar raised the demand for separate electorates for depressed classes; Tej Bahadur Sapru moved the All-India Federation idea", "Ambedkar demanded abolition of Diarchy; Sarojini Naidu moved the federation idea", "Ambedkar demanded Poorna Swaraj; Motilal Nehru moved the federation idea"], "correct": "2", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Ambedkar raised the demand for separate electorates for depressed classes; Tej Bahadur Sapru moved the All-India Federation idea</b><br><br>Though the First RTC was largely a failure, <b>Ambedkar</b> raised the demand for <b>separate electorates</b> for the depressed classes, and the idea of an <b>All-India Federation</b> was moved to the centre of discussion by <b>Tej Bahadur Sapru</b>. The Princely States agreed to the federation provided their internal sovereignty was guaranteed, and the Muslim League also supported it since it opposed a strong Centre. The British agreed that representative government should be introduced at the provincial level.", "expimage": ""},
"45": {"questext": "The Gandhi-Irwin Pact was signed on which date, and what did Sarojini Naidu call it?", "options": ["5 March 1931; the 'union of two Mahatmas'", "17 February 1931; the 'epoch-making event'", "26 January 1930; the 'Delhi Declaration'", "23 March 1931; the 'compromise of equals'"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>5 March 1931; the 'union of two Mahatmas'</b><br><br>After the failure of the First RTC, liberal leaders like <b>Sapru and Jayakar</b> requested Gandhi to meet the Viceroy. Talks began in Delhi on <b>17 February</b> and an agreement was signed on <b>5 March 1931</b>, known as the <b>'Gandhi-Irwin Pact'</b> (also called the <b>Delhi Pact</b>), placing the Congress on an equal footing with the Government. <b>Sarojini Naidu</b> called it the <b>'union of two Mahatmas'</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"46": {"questext": "Which of the following concessions did Lord Irwin agree to on behalf of the British Government under the Gandhi-Irwin Pact?", "options": ["Immediate release of political prisoners not convicted of violence and right to make salt in coastal villages", "Full independence for India", "Abolition of separate electorates for all communities", "Capital punishment for Bhagat Singh, Sukhdev and Rajguru to be commuted"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Immediate release of political prisoners not convicted of violence and right to make salt in coastal villages</b><br><br>Irwin agreed to: immediate release of political prisoners not convicted of violence; remission of unpaid fines; return of unsold lands; lenient treatment of resigned government servants; right to make <b>salt</b> in coastal villages for personal use; right to peaceful picketing; and withdrawal of emergency ordinances. However, Gandhi's demand for an <b>enquiry into police excesses</b> and leniency towards <b>Bhagat Singh, Sukhdev and Rajguru</b> were ignored.", "expimage": ""},
"47": {"questext": "What did Gandhi agree to on behalf of the Congress under the Gandhi-Irwin Pact, and who criticized him for this compromise?", "options": ["To suspend the Civil Disobedience Movement and participate in the next RTC; criticized by Nehru and Bose", "To launch a fresh movement; praised by Churchill", "To boycott British goods permanently; criticized by Ambedkar", "To resign from Congress presidency; criticized by Irwin"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>To suspend the Civil Disobedience Movement and participate in the next RTC; criticized by Nehru and Bose</b><br><br>Gandhi agreed to <b>suspend the civil disobedience movement</b>, to participate in the next Round Table Conference, and that Congress would not boycott British goods. Several people, including <b>Jawaharlal Nehru and Subhash Chandra Bose</b>, criticized Gandhi for compromising on the issue of Poorna Swaraj. Younger Congress members at the <b>Karachi session (1931)</b> showed black flags to Gandhi over his inability to prevent the hanging of Bhagat Singh.", "expimage": ""},
"48": {"questext": "The Karachi session of Congress in March 1931 was presided over by whom, and what did Gandhiji famously say there?", "options": ["Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel; 'Gandhi may die, but Gandhism cannot'", "Jawaharlal Nehru; 'Do or Die'", "Motilal Nehru; 'Simon Go Back'", "M.A. Ansari; 'Freedom is our birthright'"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel; 'Gandhi may die, but Gandhism cannot'</b><br><br>In March 1931, a special session of Congress was held in <b>Karachi</b>, presided over by <b>Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel</b>. The Gandhi-Irwin Pact was accepted along with Poorna Swaraj, and for the first time Congress accepted proposals on fundamental rights and national economic programs. It was at this session that Gandhiji said, <b>\"Gandhi may die, but Gandhism cannot.\"</b> K.M. Munshi called the Gandhi-Irwin Pact an 'epoch-making event'.", "expimage": ""},
"49": {"questext": "The Second Round Table Conference (Sep-Dec 1931) was held in London. Who had become the Secretary of State for India and Viceroy of India at that time?", "options": ["Samuel Hoare (Secretary of State) and Wellington (Viceroy)", "Lord Birkenhead (Secretary of State) and Lord Irwin (Viceroy)", "Lord Linlithgow (Secretary of State) and Lord Willingdon (Viceroy)", "Sir John Simon (Secretary of State) and Lord Curzon (Viceroy)"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Samuel Hoare (Secretary of State) and Wellington (Viceroy)</b><br><br>The Second Round Table Conference was held at <b>St. James Palace, London</b>, in December 1931. By this time, <b>Ramsay MacDonald</b> had become the Prime Minister of Britain, right-wing reactionary <b>Samuel Hoare</b> had become the Secretary of India, and <b>Wellington</b> had become the Viceroy of India. Gandhiji travelled to the conference on the ship <b>'Rajputana'</b>, accompanied by <b>Mahadev Desai, Madan Mohan Malviya, Devdas Gandhi, G.D. Birla, Mira Ben</b> and <b>Sarojini Naidu</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"50": {"questext": "What were Gandhi's key demands at the Second Round Table Conference?", "options": ["Immediate responsible government and that Congress alone represented India, with no separate electorates for minorities", "Continuation of Diarchy and separate electorates for all communities", "Dominion status only, without responsible government", "Abolition of the Congress party in favour of the Muslim League"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Immediate responsible government and that Congress alone represented India, with no separate electorates for minorities</b><br><br>Gandhi's demands at the Second RTC were: a <b>responsible government</b> at the Centre and provinces must be established immediately; <b>Congress alone represented India</b> as a nation; the <b>Untouchables</b> were Hindus and should not be treated as a minority; and there should be <b>no communal division</b> by introducing separate electorates for Muslims or other minorities.", "expimage": ""},
"51": {"questext": "Why did the Second Round Table Conference fail?", "options": ["Due to a dispute over the communal problem and demands for separate electorates by Muslims, Depressed classes, Christians and Anglo-Indians", "Because Congress refused to attend at all", "Because Gandhi did not travel to London", "Because the Princely States boycotted it"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Due to a dispute over the communal problem and demands for separate electorates by Muslims, Depressed classes, Christians and Anglo-Indians</b><br><br>The Right Wing in Britain led by <b>Churchill</b> objected to negotiating with Congress as an equal. Ramsay MacDonald headed a Conservative-dominated cabinet with a weak Secretary of State, Samuel Hoare. The conference became a complete failure due to the dispute over the <b>communal problem</b>, as separate electorates were demanded by <b>Muslims, Depressed classes, Christians and Anglo-Indians</b>, while Gandhi opposed such division.", "expimage": ""},
"52": {"questext": "What did Winston Churchill call Gandhiji during the Second Round Table Conference, and when did Gandhi return to Bombay?", "options": ["'Half-naked fakir'; 28 December 1931", "'Mussolini of India'; 5 March 1931", "'Frontier Gandhi'; 1 January 1932", "'Traitor to the Empire'; 17 February 1931"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>'Half-naked fakir'; 28 December 1931</b><br><br>During this conference, Winston Churchill called Gandhiji a <b>'half-naked fakir'</b>. On <b>28 December 1931</b>, Gandhi returned to Bombay empty-handed and disappointed from London, saying he was satisfied that he did not let the flag handed to him fall. After returning, Gandhiji wanted to meet Viceroy <b>Wellington</b>, but was refused a meeting, and the government effectively buried the Gandhi-Irwin Pact.", "expimage": ""},
"53": {"questext": "Who was sent to India as the new Viceroy while Gandhi was attending the Second Round Table Conference, and what did he do regarding the Gandhi-Irwin Pact?", "options": ["Lord Willingdon; he refused to accept many of its terms", "Lord Wavell; he fully honoured the pact", "Lord Linlithgow; he expanded the pact's provisions", "Lord Curzon; he negotiated a new pact"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Lord Willingdon; he refused to accept many of its terms</b><br><br>While Gandhi was attending the Second RTC, <b>Lord Willingdon</b> was sent to India as the new Viceroy. He refused to accept many terms agreed upon in the Gandhi-Irwin Pact and tried to crush discontent by force. As a result, Gandhi decided to re-start the <b>Civil Disobedience Movement in January 1932</b>, amid the continuing effects of the Great Depression.", "expimage": ""},
"54": {"questext": "During the second phase of the Civil Disobedience Movement (1932-34), how did the British government respond, and what did Lord Willingdon call Gandhi?", "options": ["The Congress was declared illegal and Gandhi was called the 'Mussolini of India'", "The government negotiated peacefully; Gandhi was praised", "The Congress was allowed to function freely without restrictions", "The government released all political prisoners immediately"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The Congress was declared illegal and Gandhi was called the 'Mussolini of India'</b><br><br>The relaunch of the Civil Disobedience Movement met severe repression; the <b>Congress was declared an illegal organization</b>, its property was confiscated, and top leaders including Gandhiji, Jawaharlal Nehru, Sardar Patel, and <b>Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan</b> were arrested — over 1 lakh persons were arrested within six months. Lord Willingdon condemned Gandhi as the <b>'Mussolini of India'</b>. While the movement was at its peak, PM Ramsay MacDonald announced the <b>'Communal Award'</b>, changing the movement's direction, and Gandhiji postponed the second CDM in <b>April 1934</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"55": {"questext": "The Communal Award was announced on 16 August 1932 by whom, and what did it provide for?", "options": ["Ramsay MacDonald; separate electorates for Muslims, Sikhs, Christians, Anglo-Indians, Europeans and special constituencies for Depressed Classes", "Lord Irwin; abolition of all separate electorates", "Lord Willingdon; universal adult suffrage", "Samuel Hoare; reservation only for women"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Ramsay MacDonald; separate electorates for Muslims, Sikhs, Christians, Anglo-Indians, Europeans and special constituencies for Depressed Classes</b><br><br>The <b>Communal Award</b> was declared by British PM <b>Ramsay MacDonald</b> on <b>16 August 1932</b>. It provided for separate electorates for <b>Muslims, Sikhs, Christians, Anglo-Indians and Europeans</b>, and assured the <b>Depressed Classes</b> separate special constituencies. Special communal constituencies were also created for <b>women</b> in all provinces except NWFP, and <b>seven seats</b> were reserved for the Marathas.", "expimage": ""},
"56": {"questext": "Why did Gandhi oppose the Communal Award, and what action did he take on 20 September 1932?", "options": ["He saw it as an attack on Indian unity and went on an indefinite fast", "He supported it fully and celebrated its announcement", "He ignored it as irrelevant to the freedom struggle", "He demanded its immediate expansion to more communities"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>He saw it as an attack on Indian unity and went on an indefinite fast</b><br><br>Gandhi saw the Communal Award as an attack on <b>Indian unity and nationalism</b>, harmful to both Hinduism and the Depressed Classes, arguing that treating them as a separate political entity would undermine the abolition of <b>untouchability</b>. He demanded the depressed classes be elected through a joint, wider electorate under universal franchise. To press this, he went on an <b>indefinite fast on 20 September 1932</b> in Yerwada jail.", "expimage": ""},
"57": {"questext": "The Poona Pact of 26 September 1932 was signed between which two leaders, with whose mediation?", "options": ["Gandhi and Ambedkar, with the efforts of Madan Mohan Malviya, Rajendra Prasad, and C. Rajagopalachari", "Nehru and Jinnah, with the efforts of Lord Irwin", "Gandhi and Jinnah, with the efforts of Sardar Patel", "Ambedkar and Jinnah, with the efforts of Sarojini Naidu"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Gandhi and Ambedkar, with the efforts of Madan Mohan Malviya, Rajendra Prasad, and C. Rajagopalachari</b><br><br>The <b>Poona Pact</b> refers to an agreement between <b>Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar</b> and <b>Mahatma Gandhi</b>, signed with the efforts of <b>Madan Mohan Malviya, Dr. Rajendra Prasad, Purushottam Das, and C. Rajagopalachari</b> in September 1932. Tagore called it 'a great sacrifice for the unity of India and its social integrity'.", "expimage": ""},
"58": {"questext": "What did the Poona Pact provide regarding reserved seats for the Depressed Classes, replacing the Communal Award?", "options": ["Seats increased from 71 to 147 in Provincial Legislatures, and 18% reserved in the Central Legislature", "Seats reduced from 147 to 71 in Provincial Legislatures", "Complete abolition of all reserved seats", "Seats increased only in the Central Legislature, not provinces"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Seats increased from 71 to 147 in Provincial Legislatures, and 18% reserved in the Central Legislature</b><br><br>The Poona Pact made two key changes to replace the Communal Award for Depressed Classes: seats reserved for the Depressed Classes were increased from <b>71 to 147</b> in Provincial Legislatures, and <b>18%</b> of total seats in the Central Legislature were reserved for them. The pact was accepted by the Government as an amendment to the Communal Award, and through it Ambedkar agreed to drop his demand for <b>separate electorates</b> in favour of seat reservations, which arguably saved the country from another partition along caste lines.", "expimage": ""},
"59": {"questext": "The Third Round Table Conference (Nov-Dec 1932) resulted in which document, and under whose chairmanship was a joint committee formed to consider it?", "options": ["White Paper (March 1933); Lord Linlithgow", "Nehru Report; Motilal Nehru", "Government of India Act 1919; Lord Birkenhead", "Simon Commission Report; Sir John Simon"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>White Paper (March 1933); Lord Linlithgow</b><br><br>The Third RTC assembled on <b>17 November 1932</b> in London with only <b>forty-six delegates</b>, since Congress did not participate. After this conference, the British drafted proposals for constitutional reforms embodied in the <b>White Paper</b> published in <b>March 1933</b>. A joint committee of the British Parliament under <b>Lord Linlithgow</b> considered the White Paper, and based on its report, a bill was introduced by <b>Samuel Hoare</b>, eventually passed as the <b>Government of India Act, 1935</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"60": {"questext": "Who established the Congress Socialist Party in Bombay in 1934?", "options": ["Jai Prakash Narayan, Acharya Narendra Dev and Minoo Masani", "M.N. Roy, S.A. Dange and Muzaffar Ahmad", "Subhash Chandra Bose and Sardar Patel", "Motilal Nehru and Tej Bahadur Sapru"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Jai Prakash Narayan, Acharya Narendra Dev and Minoo Masani</b><br><br>In 1934, a large section of the Congress stressed forming a separate party to propagate socialist ideology within the Congress. For this purpose, <b>Jai Prakash Narayan, Acharya Narendra Dev, and Minoo Masani</b> established the <b>'Congress Socialist Party'</b> in Bombay, with supporting leaders including <b>Ashok Mehta, Achyut Patwardhan, and Dr. Ram Manohar Lohia</b>. The goal of socialism was set at the <b>Lucknow session of Congress in 1936</b>, though Nehru's related proposal was rejected by the Congress Working Committee.", "expimage": ""},
"61": {"questext": "Why did the Civil Disobedience Movement lose momentum by the beginning of 1934?", "options": ["Government oppression was more determined and the movement's orientation shifted to the Communal Award issue and later the Bihar earthquake relief efforts", "The British granted complete independence", "Gandhi joined the government", "The Congress was dissolved permanently"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Government oppression was more determined and the movement's orientation shifted to the Communal Award issue and later the Bihar earthquake relief efforts</b><br><br>The second phase of CDM could not create the same enthusiasm; government oppression was more determined, and the movement lost orientation due to the pressing Communal Award issue. On <b>1 August 1933</b>, Gandhi launched <b>individual Satyagraha</b> to maintain momentum without disrupting daily life. Bihar was hit by a devastating <b>earthquake in 1934</b>, and Congress dedicated its efforts to relief work, after which Gandhi withdrew from active politics to focus on the welfare of Harijans.", "expimage": ""},
"62": {"questext": "Which of the following was among the achievements of the Civil Disobedience Movement, according to its critical appraisal?", "options": ["It marked the beginning of India's struggle for complete independence and united different classes in a common campaign", "It led to the immediate grant of Dominion Status", "It ended communal tensions in India permanently", "It resulted in the abolition of the salt tax"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>It marked the beginning of India's struggle for complete independence and united different classes in a common campaign</b><br><br>Though the CDM failed to achieve Poorna Swaraj, it marked the beginning of India's struggle for complete independence, integrated various levels of political awareness, and united different classes and groups. It was actively supported by leftists, industrial workers, peasants, and tribals, including the <b>Tana Bhagat movement</b>, the <b>Naga movement under Rani Gaidinliu</b>, and industrialists like <b>Jamnalal Bajaj and G.D. Birla</b>. Students were called the 'backbone' of the movement.", "expimage": ""},
"63": {"questext": "What was significant about the Civil Disobedience Movement's reach into Princely States and its overall standing among national movements?", "options": ["It was the first movement to reach Princely States and unite Praja Mandal Movements with the national movement, and was the longest and most widely participated movement", "It never reached the Princely States at all", "It was the shortest movement in Indian history", "It excluded all workers and students"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>It was the first movement to reach Princely States and unite Praja Mandal Movements with the national movement, and was the longest and most widely participated movement</b><br><br>The CDM was the first movement to reach the <b>Princely States</b>, successfully uniting the <b>Praja Mandal Movements</b> with the national movement, proving India's determination to secure freedom. Despite being suspended twice, it was the first nationwide, most widely participated, and longest movement of its time.", "expimage": ""},
"64": {"questext": "What was Gandhi's Harijan Programme, and what was his new body first named before being renamed the Harijan Sevak Sangh?", "options": ["All India Anti-Untouchability League, set up in October 1932", "Kasturba Balika Ashram, set up in 1930", "Congress Socialist Party, set up in 1934", "National Planning Committee, set up in 1938"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>All India Anti-Untouchability League, set up in October 1932</b><br><br>After 1931, to better organize the campaign for the upliftment of Untouchables, Gandhi set up a new body in <b>October 1932</b>, first named the <b>All India Anti-Untouchability League</b>, later renamed the <b>Harijan Sevak Sangh</b>. Local branches were set up in the provinces while the central body was in Mumbai. <b>'Harijan'</b> meant 'People of God', and the Sangh provided financial assistance and scholarships to Harijan students.", "expimage": ""},
"65": {"questext": "Who gave the name 'Harijan' to the Dalit classes, and when did he start the Harijan Yatra?", "options": ["Gandhiji; started from Wardha on 7 November 1933", "Ambedkar; started from Poona on 26 September 1932", "Nehru; started from Delhi in 1929", "Rajendra Prasad; started from Karachi in 1931"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Gandhiji; started from Wardha on 7 November 1933</b><br><br>It was <b>Gandhiji</b> who gave the name <b>'Harijan'</b> to the Dalit classes. After the Poona Pact, his interest in the anti-untouchability movement increased, and he founded the <b>Harijan Sevak Sangh</b>. In September 1932, he also founded the All India Anti-Untouchability League and published a weekly paper called <b>'Harijan'</b>. On <b>7 November 1933</b>, Gandhiji started the <b>Harijan Yatra</b> from Wardha, travelling 20,000 km over about 9 months, during which he faced black flags and disrupted meetings.", "expimage": ""},
"66": {"questext": "Where did Gandhi play a central role in opening a famous temple to untouchables, and with whom did he plan a fast unto death if it remained closed?", "options": ["Guruvayur temple in Kerala; with K. Kelappan", "Jagannath temple in Puri; with Ambedkar", "Somnath temple in Gujarat; with Rajendra Prasad", "Kashi Vishwanath temple; with Sardar Patel"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Guruvayur temple in Kerala; with K. Kelappan</b><br><br>Gandhi initiated the movement to open public temples to untouchables and played a central role in opening the famous temple at <b>Guruvayur</b> in Kerala. In early 1932, he declared his intention, along with satyagrahi leader <b>K. Kelappan</b>, to undertake a fast unto death from <b>1 January 1933</b> if the temple was not opened. In early February 1933, with help from G.D. Birla, R.V. Sastri and Mahadev Desai, he brought out the weekly journal <b>'Harijan'</b> in English, with vernacular editions following by March.", "expimage": ""},
"67": {"questext": "On 1 August 1933, Gandhi dedicated which ashram for the exclusive use of Harijans, and where were institutions like the Kasturba Balika Ashram and Harijan Balika Vidyalaya set up?", "options": ["Sabarmati Ashram; Kasturba Balika Ashram in Delhi and Harijan Balika Vidyalaya at Sabarmati", "Wardha Ashram; both in Wardha", "Yerwada Ashram; both in Poona", "Sevagram Ashram; both in Bombay"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Sabarmati Ashram; Kasturba Balika Ashram in Delhi and Harijan Balika Vidyalaya at Sabarmati</b><br><br>On <b>1 August 1933</b>, with the concurrence of his co-trustees, Gandhi dedicated the <b>Sabarmati Ashram</b> for the exclusive use of Harijans. Institutions for girl students such as the <b>Kasturba Balika Ashram in Delhi</b> and <b>Harijan Balika Vidyalaya at Sabarmati</b> were also set up, alongside training institutions in cottage industries, making removal of untouchability a chief plank of Gandhi's programme.", "expimage": ""},
"68": {"questext": "The Government of India Act, 1935 provided for provincial autonomy. When did it come into operation, though the federal part was never introduced?", "options": ["1937", "1935", "1930", "1940"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>1937</b><br><br>The Government of India Act, 1935 had provisions for an all-India federation and provincial autonomy. Although the federal part was never introduced, <b>provincial autonomy came into operation from 1937</b>, motivating the rise of many political parties. Congress President <b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b> agreed that Congress had limited options and had to fight the elections.", "expimage": ""},
"69": {"questext": "What was the Congress's approach while contesting the 1937 provincial elections?", "options": ["To contest with a negative manifesto of uncompromising hostility to the Act, aiming to educate the masses rather than seek power", "To fully cooperate with the Government of India Act, 1935", "To boycott the elections entirely", "To merge with the Muslim League for the elections"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>To contest with a negative manifesto of uncompromising hostility to the Act, aiming to educate the masses rather than seek power</b><br><br>The Congress decided to contest with a <b>negative manifesto</b> — an attitude of uncompromising hostility towards the Government of India Act, 1935. Its approach was not to seek power but to <b>educate the masses</b> on political and economic programmes and move towards framing a new Constitution of India. At the <b>Lucknow and Faizabad session (1936)</b>, chaired by Jawaharlal Nehru, all factions agreed to take part in the elections.", "expimage": ""},
"70": {"questext": "Which parties were formed by Fazlul Huq and Dr. Ambedkar respectively ahead of the 1937 elections?", "options": ["Fazlul Huq formed the Krishak Praja Party; Ambedkar launched the Independent Labour Party", "Fazlul Huq formed the Muslim League; Ambedkar launched the Congress Socialist Party", "Fazlul Huq formed the Unionist Party; Ambedkar launched the Forward Bloc", "Fazlul Huq formed the Justice Party; Ambedkar launched the Hindu Mahasabha"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Fazlul Huq formed the Krishak Praja Party; Ambedkar launched the Independent Labour Party</b><br><br><b>Fazlul Huq</b> formed the <b>'Krishak Praja Party'</b>, while <b>Dr. Ambedkar</b> launched the <b>'Independent Labour Party'</b> in the Central Provinces and Bengal. The results of the 1937 elections were declared in <b>February 1937</b>. Ambedkar's Independent Labour Party secured 14 out of 17 contested seats, including 11 of 13 reserved seats and 3 of 4 general seats.", "expimage": ""},
"71": {"questext": "Which parties formed the government in Punjab and Bengal after the 1937 elections, since these were the only non-Congress ministries (along with Sindh)?", "options": ["Unionist Party (Punjab, under Sikander Hyat Khan) and Krishak Praja Party coalition (Bengal, under A.K. Fazlul Huq)", "Congress in both Punjab and Bengal", "Muslim League alone in both provinces", "Hindu Mahasabha in Punjab and Congress in Bengal"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Unionist Party (Punjab, under Sikander Hyat Khan) and Krishak Praja Party coalition (Bengal, under A.K. Fazlul Huq)</b><br><br>The <b>Unionist Party</b> under <b>Sikander Hyat Khan</b> formed the government in Punjab with 95 of 175 seats. In Bengal, though Congress was the largest party with 52 seats, the <b>Krishak Praja Party</b> of <b>A.K. Fazlul Huq</b> (36 seats) formed a coalition government. Congress was deprived of a majority only in <b>Bengal, Punjab and Sindh</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"72": {"questext": "In how many provinces did Congress form its government after the 1937 elections, and what was the Central Control Council formed to manage them called?", "options": ["8 provinces; Parliamentary Sub-Committee", "5 provinces; Central Advisory Council", "11 provinces; National Coordination Committee", "3 provinces; Congress High Command"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>8 provinces; Parliamentary Sub-Committee</b><br><br>Congress formed governments in <b>Madras, United Province, Central Province, Bihar, Bombay, Orissa</b>, and later in <b>North-West Frontier Province and Assam</b> — a total of <b>8 provinces</b>. A Central Control Council, the <b>Parliamentary Sub-Committee</b>, was formed with members <b>Sardar Patel, Maulana Abul Kalam Azad, and Dr. Rajendra Prasad</b>. Provincial chiefs were at this time called <b>Prime Ministers</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"73": {"questext": "What condition did Jinnah insist on for a Congress-Muslim League coalition after the 1937 elections, which Congress rejected?", "options": ["Congress should not nominate any Muslim to the ministries", "Congress should dissolve the Parliamentary Sub-Committee", "Congress should accept separate electorates for all provinces", "Congress should hand over the presidency to Jinnah"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Congress should not nominate any Muslim to the ministries</b><br><br>The 1937 election results widened the rift between Congress and the Muslim League, which fared badly even in Muslim-majority provinces. <b>Jinnah</b> offered to form coalitions with Congress but insisted that <b>Congress should not nominate any Muslim to the ministries</b>, as the League claimed to be the exclusive representative of Indian Muslims — a condition unacceptable to Congress. Congress President <b>Subhash Chandra Bose</b> appointed the <b>National Planning Committee</b> in 1938, chaired by <b>J.L. Nehru</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"74": {"questext": "Who served as Prime Minister of Madras and Bombay respectively under the Congress provincial governments of 1937?", "options": ["C. Rajagopalachari (Madras) and B.G. Kher (Bombay)", "Govind Vallabh Pant (Madras) and Srikrishna Sinha (Bombay)", "Fazlul Haq (Madras) and Sikandar Hayat Khan (Bombay)", "Allah Baksh (Madras) and Dr. Khan Sahab (Bombay)"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>C. Rajagopalachari (Madras) and B.G. Kher (Bombay)</b><br><br>Prime Ministers of the provinces included: <b>Madras — C. Rajagopalachari</b>; <b>Bihar — Srikrishna Sinha</b>; <b>Orissa — B.N. Das</b>; <b>Central Province — N.B. Khare</b> (later Ravi Shankar Shukla); <b>United Province — Govind Vallabh Pant</b>; <b>Bombay — B.G. Kher</b>; <b>Assam — Saadulla</b> (later Gopinath Bardolai); <b>North Western Province — Dr. Khan Sahab</b>; <b>Sindh — Allah Baksh</b>; <b>Bengal — Fazlul Haq</b>; and <b>Punjab — Sikandar Hayat Khan</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"75": {"questext": "Which of the following was an achievement of the Congress governments during their 1937-39 tenure?", "options": ["Tackling elementary education, industrial wages, cottage industries and release of political prisoners", "Complete abolition of the caste system", "Introduction of universal adult franchise", "Full independence from British rule"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Tackling elementary education, industrial wages, cottage industries and release of political prisoners</b><br><br>The Congress governments tackled elementary education, industrial wages, cottage industries, and upliftment of Harijans; provided relief to peasants from indebtedness; passed <b>tenancy laws</b> to benefit farmers; and took up the cause of political prisoners, ensuring most were released and their properties restored.", "expimage": ""},
"76": {"questext": "What criticism did the Congress ministries (1937-39) face, and which act resulted from the anti-labour shift in Congress attitudes?", "options": ["Criticism over limited removal of caste disabilities; Bombay Traders Disputes Act, 1938", "Criticism for granting full independence too quickly; Trade Unions Act, 1926", "Criticism for banning all trade unions; Communal Award", "Criticism for abolishing zamindari; Poona Pact"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Criticism over limited removal of caste disabilities; Bombay Traders Disputes Act, 1938</b><br><br>Dalits and their leaders were unimpressed with the removal of only a few caste-based disabilities and limited temple entry bills. Congress victories aroused hopes of the industrial working class, leading to increased industrial unrest, but Congress's closer relationship with Indian Capitalists resulted in an <b>anti-labour shift</b>, leading to the <b>Bombay Traders Disputes Act, 1938</b>. The Muslim League also charged the Congress ministries with being pro-Hindu.", "expimage": ""},
"77": {"questext": "When did Viceroy Linlithgow declare India at war with the Axis Powers, and how did Congress respond?", "options": ["3 September 1939; Congress objected strongly to the declaration without prior consultation with Indians", "1 September 1939; Congress welcomed the declaration", "26 January 1930; Congress ignored it", "5 March 1931; Congress supported it fully"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>3 September 1939; Congress objected strongly to the declaration without prior consultation with Indians</b><br><br>Viceroy <b>Linlithgow</b> declared India at war with the Axis Powers on <b>3 September 1939</b> without consulting Indian leaders. The Congress objected strongly and the Congress Working Committee suggested it would cooperate only if a Central Indian national government were formed and independence committed to after the war.", "expimage": ""},
"78": {"questext": "How did the Muslim League respond to the outbreak of WWII compared to the Congress, and what followed on 22 October 1939?", "options": ["The League promised support to the British while Congress ministries resigned, celebrated by the League as a 'Day of Deliverance'", "Both Congress and the League resigned together", "The League also resigned in protest", "Congress supported the war fully while the League opposed it"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The League promised support to the British while Congress ministries resigned, celebrated by the League as a 'Day of Deliverance'</b><br><br>The <b>Muslim League</b> promised support to the British, with <b>Jinnah</b> calling on Muslims for 'honourable co-operation' while seeking increased protection for Muslims. <b>Linlithgow</b> refused Congress's demands, so on <b>22 October 1939</b>, Congress ministries tendered their resignations, which the Muslim League celebrated as a <b>'day of deliverance'</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"79": {"questext": "Where was the 1939 Congress session held that led to the 'Tripuri Crisis', and who had been the unanimous choice for president at the 1938 Haripura session?", "options": ["Tripuri, Jabalpur district (present-day Madhya Pradesh); Subhash Chandra Bose", "Lahore; Jawaharlal Nehru", "Karachi; Sardar Patel", "Lucknow; Motilal Nehru"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Tripuri, Jabalpur district (present-day Madhya Pradesh); Subhash Chandra Bose</b><br><br>The Congress Session of 1939 was held in <b>Tripuri</b>, a small village in the district of Jabalpur, present-day Madhya Pradesh. <b>Subhash Chandra Bose</b> had been the unanimous choice as President at the <b>1938 Haripura Session</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"80": {"questext": "In the 1939 Tripuri Congress, whom did Subhash Chandra Bose defeat to be elected president for the second time, and what did Gandhi say about it?", "options": ["Pattabhi Sitaramayya; Gandhi declared Sitaramayya's defeat was his own defeat", "Jawaharlal Nehru; Gandhi congratulated Bose", "Sardar Patel; Gandhi remained silent", "Rajendra Prasad; Gandhi called it a fair contest"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Pattabhi Sitaramayya; Gandhi declared Sitaramayya's defeat was his own defeat</b><br><br>At the Tripuri Congress (1939), Subhash Chandra Bose defeated Gandhiji's favourite candidate <b>Pattabhi Sitaramayya</b> to become president for the second time. Gandhi declared that <b>Sitaramayya's defeat was his own defeat</b>. A resolution was passed asking the President to appoint Working Committee members as per Gandhiji's wishes, but Gandhiji refused to give advice.", "expimage": ""},
"81": {"questext": "What did Subhash Chandra Bose do after resigning from the post of Congress President in April 1939?", "options": ["He founded the Forward Bloc in 1939 and was declared ineligible for any Congress post for three years", "He rejoined the Congress Working Committee immediately", "He joined the Muslim League", "He became the Viceroy's advisor"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>He founded the Forward Bloc in 1939 and was declared ineligible for any Congress post for three years</b><br><br>Following disagreement over Working Committee appointments, Subhash Chandra Bose resigned from the post of Congress President in <b>April 1939</b>. <b>Dr. Rajendra Prasad</b> was made the President in his place, and it was followed by the resignation of all Working Committee members. After separating from Congress, Bose founded the <b>Forward Bloc in 1939</b> and was declared ineligible for any Congress post for three years.", "expimage": ""},
"82": {"questext": "Where did the Communist ideology gain ground in India after the First World War, and who propagated left-wing ideology through their respective publications?", "options": ["Industrial centres like Bombay, Calcutta, Madras; Ghulam Hussain ('Inquilab'), S.A. Dange ('Socialist'), Muzaffar Ahmad ('Navyug')", "Rural areas only; Gandhi through 'Harijan'", "Only in Bengal; Subhash Chandra Bose through 'Forward Bloc'", "Princely states; Ambedkar through 'Independent Labour Party'"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Industrial centres like Bombay, Calcutta, Madras; Ghulam Hussain ('Inquilab'), S.A. Dange ('Socialist'), Muzaffar Ahmad ('Navyug')</b><br><br>In India, Communist ideology gained ground after the First World War, especially at industrial centres like <b>Bombay, Calcutta, Madras, Lahore, and Kanpur</b>. <b>Ghulam Hussain</b> in Mumbai via his <b>'Inquilab'</b>, <b>S.A. Dange</b> via <b>'Socialist'</b>, and <b>Muzaffar Ahmad</b> in Bengal via his <b>'Navyug'</b> propagated left-wing ideology among the masses.", "expimage": ""},
"83": {"questext": "Which of the following was a factor leading to the rise of the Left Movement in India?", "options": ["Success of the Bolshevik Revolution in Russia and economic burdens of the First World War", "The signing of the Poona Pact", "The Government of India Act, 1919", "The failure of the Simon Commission alone"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Success of the Bolshevik Revolution in Russia and economic burdens of the First World War</b><br><br>Factors leading to the rise of the Left Movement included: the success of the <b>Bolshevik Revolution</b> in Russia; the crippling economic burden of the <b>First World War</b>; the rise of peasant and worker movements; the educated Indian <b>middle class</b> facing unemployment; and the objections of the Leftists to <b>Gandhian Swaraj</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"84": {"questext": "Who declared the formation of the Communist Party of India (CPI), and where and when?", "options": ["M.N. Roy and supporters; Tashkent, Russia, October 1920", "S.A. Dange and supporters; Kanpur, December 1925", "Muzaffar Ahmad; Calcutta, 1922", "Ghulam Hussain; Bombay, 1919"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>M.N. Roy and supporters; Tashkent, Russia, October 1920</b><br><br><b>M.N. Roy</b> and a few of his supporters declared the formation of the <b>Communist Party of India (CPI)</b> in <b>Tashkent, Russia (then U.S.S.R.)</b> in <b>October 1920</b>. This was only the beginning; for the next five years, various Communist groups were launched across India, most of which came together in <b>Kanpur in December 1925</b> to found an all-India organization under the name Communist Party of India.", "expimage": ""},
"85": {"questext": "When was the CPI banned by the British, and what did Communists do after the ban was imposed?", "options": ["Banned in 1934; many Communists infiltrated into the Congress", "Banned in 1925; Communists formed the Muslim League", "Banned in 1920; Communists left India entirely", "Banned in 1939; Communists joined the Forward Bloc exclusively"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Banned in 1934; many Communists infiltrated into the Congress</b><br><br>British authorities, alarmed by the rising tide of the Communist Movement, banned the CPI in <b>1934</b>. During its initial years, the CPI launched peasants' and workers' movements and organized industrial strikes. When the official ban was imposed, many Communists infiltrated into the <b>Congress</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"86": {"questext": "How did the Moderate Congress leaders and the CPI respectively characterize the Congress Socialists, and at which sessions did Subhash Chandra Bose's presidency mark a victory for them?", "options": ["Moderates called them 'internationalists', CPI called them 'fake socialists'; Haripura (1938) and Tripuri (1939) sessions", "Moderates praised them fully, CPI ignored them; Lahore session (1929)", "Both Moderates and CPI supported them equally; Karachi session (1931)", "Moderates called them 'true nationalists', CPI called them 'traitors'; Lucknow session (1936)"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Moderates called them 'internationalists', CPI called them 'fake socialists'; Haripura (1938) and Tripuri (1939) sessions</b><br><br>Congress members inspired by left ideology were known as <b>Congress-Socialists</b>, standing for complete independence, socialism, and Swaraj for the masses. The Moderate Congress leaders called them <b>'internationalists'</b> while the CPI condemned them as <b>'fake socialists'</b>. The election of <b>Subhash Chandra Bose</b> at the <b>Haripura (1938)</b> and <b>Tripuri (1939)</b> sessions as President was a major victory for the Congress-Socialists, overshadowing Gandhi's image.", "expimage": ""},
"87": {"questext": "The Congress Socialist Party included advocates of both armed struggle and non-violent resistance. Which leaders insisted on Ahimsa within the party?", "options": ["Acharya Narendra Deva, Jayaprakash Narayana, Ram Manohar Lohia", "M.N. Roy, S.A. Dange, Muzaffar Ahmad", "Ghulam Hussain, N. Dutt Mazumdar, Ajit Roy", "Subhash Chandra Bose, Saumyendranath Tagore, Indra Sen"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Acharya Narendra Deva, Jayaprakash Narayana, Ram Manohar Lohia</b><br><br>Influenced by both <b>Fabian socialism</b> and Marxism-Leninism, the Congress Socialist Party included advocates of armed struggle or sabotage as well as those who insisted upon <b>Ahimsa</b> or non-violent resistance, such as <b>Acharya Narendra Deva, Jayaprakash Narayana, and Ram Manohar Lohia</b>. In 1934, these Congress-Socialists organized their convention in <b>Patna</b> where they enunciated a 15-point political programme.", "expimage": ""},
"88": {"questext": "According to the 15-point programme adopted at the 1934 Patna convention of Congress Socialists, what economic measures were advocated?", "options": ["Planned economic development by the State, redistribution of land among peasants, and liquidation of peasant/worker debts", "Complete privatization of all industries", "Abolition of all cooperative societies", "Continuation of Zamindari and unrestricted foreign trade"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Planned economic development by the State, redistribution of land among peasants, and liquidation of peasant/worker debts</b><br><br>The 15-point programme advocated development of the country's economic life to be planned by the <b>State</b>, State monopoly on foreign trade, and organization of co-operative societies. It adopted redistribution of <b>land</b> among peasants and liquidation of debts owed by peasants and workers, aiming to organize workers and peasants for their own economic upliftment through gradual social reforms.", "expimage": ""},
"89": {"questext": "According to the 15-point programme, what was the Congress Socialist Party's position on the Second World War and Hindu-Muslim unity?", "options": ["They opposed conditional support to the British during WWII and argued Hindu-Muslim unity should be achieved through shared economic issues, not compromise", "They fully supported British participation in WWII", "They supported the Congress-Muslim League accord on Pakistan", "They believed Hindu-Muslim unity could only be achieved through separate electorates"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>They opposed conditional support to the British during WWII and argued Hindu-Muslim unity should be achieved through shared economic issues, not compromise</b><br><br>The Congress Socialists did not support extending conditional support to the British Government during WWII, arguing the war provided a golden opportunity for direct mass struggle for independence. They argued <b>Hindu-Muslim Unity</b> could be achieved not by compromise but by stressing economic issues affecting both communities equally, and did not favour the Congress-Muslim League accord on <b>Pakistan</b>. They were more influenced by Western liberalism than Marxian Communism and disagreed with Marx that change could come only through violent means, though they continued to link their philosophy with Indian nationalism.", "expimage": ""},
"90": {"questext": "Besides the Forward Bloc (1939), which other left political parties emerged, and who founded them?", "options": ["Bolshevik Party (N. Dutt Mazumdar, 1939), Revolutionary Communist Party (Saumyendranath Tagore, 1942), Bolshevik Leninist Party (Ajit Roy and Indra Sen), Radical Democratic Party (M.N. Roy, 1940)", "Congress Socialist Party (Gandhi, 1930), CPI (Nehru, 1925)", "Muslim League Left Wing (Jinnah, 1935), Hindu Mahasabha Left (Savarkar, 1937)", "Krishak Praja Party (Fazlul Huq, left faction, 1938)"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Bolshevik Party (N. Dutt Mazumdar, 1939), Revolutionary Communist Party (Saumyendranath Tagore, 1942), Bolshevik Leninist Party (Ajit Roy and Indra Sen), Radical Democratic Party (M.N. Roy, 1940)</b><br><br>The <b>Forward Bloc</b>, established by Subhash Chandra Bose in 1939, was one of several important left parties. <b>N. Dutt Mazumdar</b> established the <b>Bolshevik Party</b> in 1939, while <b>Saumyendranath Tagore</b> founded the <b>Revolutionary Communist Party</b> in 1942. The <b>'Bolshevik Leninist Party'</b> was founded by <b>Ajit Roy and Indra Sen</b>, and <b>M.N. Roy</b> founded the <b>'Radical Democratic Party'</b> in 1940.", "expimage": ""},
"91": {"questext": "What role did the Congress Socialists play in the national movement, and which party did towering Congress-Socialist leaders form after independence?", "options": ["Led roles in the Civil Disobedience Movement, Kisan Sabha Movements and Quit India Movement; formed the Kisan Mazdoor Praja Party", "They boycotted all movements; formed the Muslim League", "They only participated in the Simon Commission protests; formed the Forward Bloc", "They joined the British Indian Army; formed the Unionist Party"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Led roles in the Civil Disobedience Movement, Kisan Sabha Movements and Quit India Movement; formed the Kisan Mazdoor Praja Party</b><br><br>The Congress Socialists played a leading role in the <b>Civil Disobedience Movement</b>, made immense contributions to the <b>Kisan Sabha Movements</b>, and played a very important role in the <b>Quit India movement</b>. At independence, towering leaders like <b>Acharya Narendra Dev, Achyut Patwardhan, Jaiprakash Narayan, Ram Manohar Lohia, J.B. Kriplani, and Ashok Mehta</b> walked out of Congress and formed the <b>Kisan Mazdoor Praja Party</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"92": {"questext": "Who founded the first modern-day labour union in India, the Madras Labour Union, and which body did the establishment of the ILO in 1919 lead to?", "options": ["B.P. Wadia; All India Trade Union Congress (AITUC)", "N.M. Joshi; National Trade Unions Federation", "Lala Lajpat Rai; Congress Socialist Party", "V.V. Giri; All India Red Trade Union Congress"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>B.P. Wadia; All India Trade Union Congress (AITUC)</b><br><br>The first modern-day labour union was established by <b>B.P. Wadia</b>, who founded the <b>Madras Labour Union</b>. The foundation of the <b>International Labour Organization</b> in 1919, with India as one of its members, saw the establishment of the <b>All India Trade Union Congress (AITUC)</b>. Its first session was organized in <b>1922</b> at Mumbai, chaired by <b>Lala Lajpat Rai</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"93": {"questext": "Which two organizations split away from the AITUC in 1929 and 1931 respectively, and under whose leadership?", "options": ["National Trade Unions Federation (1929, N.M. Joshi and V.V. Giri) and All India Red Trade Union Congress (1931, S.V. Deshpande and B.T. Ranadive)", "Congress Socialist Party (1929, JP Narayan) and Forward Bloc (1931, Bose)", "Communist Party of India (1929, M.N. Roy) and Muslim League (1931, Jinnah)", "Krishak Praja Party (1929, Fazlul Huq) and Independent Labour Party (1931, Ambedkar)"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>National Trade Unions Federation (1929, N.M. Joshi and V.V. Giri) and All India Red Trade Union Congress (1931, S.V. Deshpande and B.T. Ranadive)</b><br><br>The Communists gained influence in the trade union movement, splitting the Trade Union Congress twice. The moderate section under <b>N.M. Joshi and V.V. Giri</b> separated to form the <b>National Trade Unions Federation (NTUF)</b> in <b>1929</b>. Another split occurred in <b>1931</b> at the Calcutta session when the extreme left wing under <b>S.V. Deshpande and B.T. Ranadive</b> broke away to form the <b>All India Red Trade Union Congress</b>. This phase is described as the <b>Period of Left-Wing Trade Unionism</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"94": {"questext": "Which two Acts passed in 1926 and 1929 gave a fillip to the growth of trade unionism, and which Act was enacted in Bombay in 1938?", "options": ["Trade Unions Act, 1926 and Trade Disputes Act, 1929; Bombay Industrial Disputes Act, 1938", "Government of India Act, 1919 and 1935", "Indian Councils Act and Rowlatt Act", "Poona Pact and Communal Award"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Trade Unions Act, 1926 and Trade Disputes Act, 1929; Bombay Industrial Disputes Act, 1938</b><br><br>The passing of the <b>Trade Unions Act, 1926</b> and the <b>Trade Disputes Act, 1929</b> gave a fillip to the growth of trade unionism in India. In 1938, one of the most significant developments was the enactment of the <b>Bombay Industrial Disputes Act, 1938</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"95": {"questext": "When did the All India Red Trade Union Congress and the National Trade Union Congress (NTUC) merge back with the AITUC, and who founded the Indian National Trade Union in 1947?", "options": ["1935 (Red TUC) and 1938 (NTUC); founded by Vallabh Bhai Patel", "1929 (Red TUC) and 1931 (NTUC); founded by N.M. Joshi", "1940 (Red TUC) and 1942 (NTUC); founded by Ambedkar", "1922 (Red TUC) and 1926 (NTUC); founded by Jawaharlal Nehru"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>1935 (Red TUC) and 1938 (NTUC); founded by Vallabh Bhai Patel</b><br><br>The All India Red Trade Union Congress merged with the AITUC in <b>1935</b>, and three years later, in <b>1938</b>, the <b>National Trade Union Congress (NTUC)</b> also allied with the AITUC. In <b>1947</b>, a significant event in the history of the trade union movement was the foundation of the <b>Indian National Trade Union</b> by <b>Vallabh Bhai Patel</b>.", "expimage": ""}
};
